******
[4] Possible cholera - Uzbekistan (Tashkent)
Date: Fri 9 Sep 2011
Source: Ferghana.ru [abstracted by submitter, edited]
http://www.fergananews.com/


An epidemic of an unknown disease with symptoms of cholera has been
raging for over 20 days in the town of Yangiyol in Uzbekistan's
Tashkent Region [near the capital Tashkent].

A Ferghana correspondent on 8 Sep 2011 visited Yangiyol to check the
validity of the rumours about a possible epidemic of cholera in the
town. Announcements are posted on the doors of practically all cafes
and shops calling on the locals to thoroughly wash their hands before
eating meals, fruits and vegetables, and to drink only boiled water.

Doctors at the Yangiyol hospital did not comment on what type of
enteric disease has affected so many people or mention the name of the
disease. However, one of the medical staff on condition of anonymity
said that starting from 15 Aug 2011, several dozen people have been
taken to the hospital every day with symptoms of the disease.

"Their ages range from small children to mature men and women. All
were in a grave condition, could not walk or even stand, and had
constant diarrhea and vomiting. The whole hospital stank of rotten
fish. The nurses constantly washed them," he said.

According to the source, the doctors were banned from diagnosing [the
disease] as cholera. "A woman from Xalqobod [a settlement in the town]
with the same symptoms by herself went to a clinic of infectious
diseases in Tashkent city, where she was immediately diagnosed with
cholera," he said.

He said that towards the end of August 2011, more and more sick people
were admitted every day. "It reached a peak on 31 Aug 2011: 70 people
with similar symptoms were taken to the hospital. Only the existing
staff worked at the hospital those days. No one was sent in to help,
only those who were on leave or sick leave were called in to work,"
the hospital staff member complained.

The majority of the patients are residents of Xalqobod. "The Bozsuv
canal flows there, and many [of the patients] had swum in it. Some had
washed dishes and some their hands," the source explained.

--
